MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Gemini-Titan 3 historic mission.

[Notes: 1) The only audio that exist for this mission are recordings where the mission control loop can be heard, and is mixed with the air/ground loop. On-board tape recording does not exist to my knowledge.]
[2) This mission uses a realistic OAMS translation force. OAMS burns will be longer.]
[3) GT-3 did not have a tape loader for the OBC as all programs fit in the memory (it only used PRE-LN, ASC, CATCH-UP and RE-ENTRY) - programs will load instantly in this mission.]
TC, spacecraft going internal power.
[TC] Roger.
CM2, 4 main battery switches, ON.
Roger, 4 main battery switches on, got a main battery green light.
Roger, bring the 3 squib battery switches ON, one at a time.
Roger, 3 squibs going ON.
Can we go to internal at this time?
Roger.
Okay, let's get an internal power status check.
Main voltage is 26.
C is 25.5
[Power the computer]
[Power the MDIU]
CM2, verify the following switch configuration. Attitude control to Reentry Rate Command.
Roger, Rate Command Reentry.
RCS Ring A - Off (Closed)
Ring A is off.
RCS Ring B - Off (Closed)
RCS Ring B is off.
CM1, Booster Squib to ARM.
Squibs to ARM. [Garble]
CM1, Retro Rocket Squib switches No. 1, 2, 3 and 4, to ARM.
One, ARM.
Two, ARM.
Three, ARM.
Four, ARM.
Reset DCS, CM2.
CM2, Reset.
CM2, read out the following indications. RCS B temperature.
CSP, temperature is 80, pressure is 2650.
Understand.
CM2, standby to close the RCS ring B motorized valve by placing the propellant RCS switch to ON (open) for manual hand fire.
CM2, Wilco.
CM2, RCS ring B switch to ACME.
RCS ring B switch is ACME.
CM1, on your mark, give us two 1.5 second bursts of pitch down.
Roger.
[They will now check the RCS. Press MARK to begin.]
Two, One, MARK.
[Press [W] to pitch down, and hold it for 1.5 seconds. Release the stick and repeat the burst for another 1.5 seconds. Press ROGER when complete]
It's go.
Oh, roger. CM1, on your mark give us a two 1.5 second bursts of pitch up.
Roger.
[Press [S] to pitch up, and hold it for 1.5 seconds. Release the stick and repeat the burst for another 1.5 seconds. Press ROGER when complete]
Sounded okay.
Give us a two 1.5 second bursts of yaw left.
Roger.
[Press [A] to yaw left, and hold it for 1.5 seconds. Release the stick and repeat the burst for another 1.5 seconds. Press ROGER when complete]
It's go.
And two 1.5 second bursts of yaw right.
[Press [D] to yaw right, and hold it for 1.5 seconds. Release the stick and repeat the burst for another 1.5 seconds. Press ROGER when complete]
It's go.
CM2, RCS ring B switch to OFF.
Ring B is OFF.
OAMS fuel, temperature and pressure?
Fuel is 78, pressure is 310(0).
And give us an OAMS propellant quantity.
Propellant quantity is 94% (100% in this game).
Understand, 94.
CM2, OAMS power switch to maneuver and attitude.
Roger, OAMS power switch, maneuver and attitude.
Standby to close the OAMS motorized valves by putting the OAMS propellant switch to ON for the manual hand fire.
Roger.
CM1, on your mark, two 1.5 second bursts of yaw left.
Roger.
[Press [A] to yaw left, and hold it for 1.5 seconds. Release the stick and repeat the burst for another 1.5 seconds. Press ROGER when complete]
Alright, we need some more on that one Gus.
[Again, press [A] to yaw left, and hold it for 1.5 seconds. Release the stick and repeat the burst for another 1.5 seconds. Press ROGER when complete]
Can you give us a little longer burst, CM1?
[Sure. Press [A] to yaw left, and hold it for 3 seconds. Press ROGER when complete.]
Give us another longer burst like that.
[Roger. Press [A] to yaw left again, and hold it for 3 seconds. Press ROGER when complete.]
Give us another burst for about the same duration.
[Roger. Press [A] to yaw left again, and hold it for 3 seconds. Press ROGER when complete.]
CM2, OAMS power switch to OFF.
Propulsion meter selector to RCS B.
RCS B.
Attitude to rate command.
Rate command.
CM2, switch to continuous intercom push-to-talk.
Continuous intercom push-to-talk.
CM1 & 2, use psuh-to-talk for all remaining communications.
[All station report including CM1 and CM2, transmission is 40 seconds long.]
CM1 and 2, the whole crew wishes you godspeed, we'll see you back here shortly.
You said it, thanks very much George (Gordon Cooper).
Minus three minutes.
Roger, 3 minutes.
Minus 1:30, it's all yours John and Gus, how that.
Okay, receiveing.
CM1, we're comming up on one minute. Valves will be opening shortly.
[Countdown]
Bolts and lift-off.
Roger. Clock is started.
There's the roll program.
Roger. Roll.
Okay. Roll is completed.
Roger. Roll Complete.
There goes the pitch.
Roger. Pitch. you're on your way, Molly Brown.
Yeah man.
Plus 50 seconds.
Roger. Mode II delay.
Roger.
It just got quiet.
Cabin pressure relieving at 6.5.
Roger. Mode II.
Roger.
DCS update received.
Roger. Update.
You're a little bit high on the flight path, but no problem, Molly Brown.
Okay, Molly Brown's GO for staging.
Roger. Looks good from here.
Roger.
Second update received.
Roger. Update.
Okay, there was staging.
Roger. Stage.
And, we're thrusting.
Okay. Thrust looks good from here.
Horizon comes right into view.
Roger.
RGS is GO!
Looks good from here.
Oh, man! Look at that [horizon].
Steering is good from here.
Hey, we're moving right along that horizon.
Roger.
What did you say, Gordo?
Pretty big throttle you got there, huh?
Yes.
Roger. Molly Brown you're GO from here.
Roger. Molly Brown is GO.
Steering right down the old line.
Okay.
The nose dropped below the horizon a little bit. now it's back up above.
Roger. Stand by for my mark on 0.8.
Roger.
MARK 0.8.
Good show.
Roger.
[Garble] (SECO).
Roger. You are GO, Molly Brown.
[Separate from Stage II]
Okay. We are separated.
Roger. Fairings.
[Separate the fairings]
There went all fairings.
Okay, fine.
You have the IVI's?
[Take a note of the IVIs]
And the attitude on the ball is 18 nose down.
Roger. We have an 87 by 125 orbit, Molly Brown. [Your orbit will slightly differ from this.]
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Go, chief.
Roger. You have an 87 by 125 orbit. I'll get you One-Alpha shortly.
Roger.
Roger. New One-Alpha time is elapsed time of 18:12. 18 minutes, 12 seconds.
Roger. 18:12.
[Copy down the 1A time of 18 minutes, 12 seconds. Press ROGER when done]
Roger. Write fast, John.
[Note: No audio is available for on-board communication]
That horizon is right where they said it would be.
Yes.
Let's see, have we got everything on this checklist, John?
Let's see, retrorockets safe. Yes.
Sequence lights, test.
[Check sequence lights amber test]
[Check sequence lights red/green test]
Secondary O2 bottle is closed. I've got mine.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
GO, Cape CAP COM.
Look better from there than on a ballistic flight?
Say again?
Does it look better from there than on a ballistic flight?
I can't read you, Gordo.
Oh, roger. How - do - it - look?
It - look - nice!
Rog.
Cape CAP COM, Molly Brown. How do you read?
Cape CAP COM, Molly Brown. How do you read?
[Set UHF to No. 2]
I think we've lost them now. Let's leave it on adapter antenna and we'll try at Canaries.
Okay.
I'll put the mains to OFF and see what we've got.
Note: You can toggle an interactive GT-3 flight plan using [C] Mission Tools -> Cockpit Functions -> Toggle GT-3 Flight Plan.
[The next procedure is a quick battery check.]
[Check battery voltage ~24 vdc.]
[Check battery voltage ~24 vdc.]
[Check battery voltage ~24 vdc.]
[Check battery voltage ~24 vdc.]
[Return the DC VOLTS selector to C, or as desired.]
What's our time coming in to the Canaries?
Time is 14 something. Just a second. Okay, Canary is 14:50 acquisition. LOS 21:42.
Okay.
[Feel free to change control mode during the alignment maneuver to your liking.]
[Hold pitch to 0 using horizon reference and null yaw and roll FDI's. Verify with horizon. Press ROGER when ready to Align.]
I'd say I was alined pretty good, wouldn't you?
Yes.
[Hold attitude. Press ROGER when the "8" ball reaches 0, 0, 0.]
[Alignment is complete.]

MissionCommands.Comment: [Failure: Failure that applies yaw due to ECS.]

MissionCommands.Message: It wants to keep yawing us all the time.
[Enable OAMS and manually hold 0 in yaw.]
Huh?
It wants to keep yawing us all the time.
Yes.
We must have a leak.
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM. How do you read?
Canary CAP COM, this is Molly Brown. how do you read?
Roger. Read you loud and clear, Molly Brown.
We have your T/M solid and all systems look good on the ground.
I have your 2-1 time if you are ready to copy. Do you copy, Molly Brown?
[Press ROGER when you are ready to copy]

Okay. Ready with 2-1. [This is the retro and reentry information if early entry is required. It includes the V, when retroburn (RB) happens and when the sequence starts (RC). Press ROGER when ready to copy.]
Roger. V, 139. GMTRC, 15:55:47. GETRC, 01:31:47. Roll left, 55. GMTRB, 16:05:31. Roll right 65. Did you copy?
[Copy: V, 139. GMTRC, 15:55:47. GETRC, 01:31:47. Roll left, 55. GMTRB, 16:05:31. Roll right 65.]
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM. Request you place your radiator switch to the FLOW position.
Roger. Radiator is in FLOW position. It's cooling us right down too. It's working.
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM.
Go ahead.
Roger. We are standing by for your UHF Com Check, and would you place your radiator switch to your FLOW position?
Roger. John has been answering about all of those.
Roger. The radiator has been in FLOW the whole pass. The UHF has been on No. 2 the whole pass. over.
Roger. Copy you loud and clear, Molly Brown. We are standing by for your blood pressure.
Roger. Blood pressure is coming down.
I seem to have a leak. There must be a leak in one of the thrusters, because I get a continuous yaw left.
Roger. Understand that you get a continuous yaw left.
Very slight. Very slow drift.
Roger.
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM. I have your radiator temperatures, if you are ready to copy.
Roger.
Roger. your radiator outlet temperature if off-scale high. Your radiator inlet is 74.
Roger. Off-scale high. Going back to BY-PASS on radiator.
Roger. Understand.

[The next item on the flight plan is an experiment: "Sea Urchin Eggs" - I will soon share some details about it but for now, stop the event timer, and ensure it is set to count up. Then reset the Event Timer by pressing [C] to toggle the function bubbles, then click CREW MEMBERS, then COCKPIT FUNCTIONS -> RESET EVENT TIMER TO 00:00.]
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM. Stand by to start your clock at 20 minutes ground elapsed time. On my mark.
MARK! Did you copy, Molly Brown?
Roger. I copied, and sea urchin eggs activated.
[This marks the beginning of an experiment: Sea Urchin Eggs - it is not simulated but I include the conversation and some information about it.]

[The Sea Urchin Eggs experiment is NASAs first fundamental space biology experiment in orbit. On-board is a canister containing sea urchin eggs, Arbacia punctulata, where a handle will activate the device.]

[The canister has eight identical chambers housing sea urchin eggs and sperm. When the handle is turned, specific chambers will initiate fertilization, and then a fixative will halt cell division at different stages throughout the flight.]
[The goal of the experiment is to study the effects of subgravity on fertilization, cell division, differentation, and growth of a relatively simple biological system
[Next on the flight plan is a Control Systems Check where the +/- pitch, yaw and roll will be tested in Direct Mode and in Rate Command Mode. Press ROGER to start]
[Press and hold [S] for 1 second to pitch up.]
[Press and hold [W] for 2 second to stop pitch up rates and build up a pitch down rate.]
[Stop the pitch rates.]
[Press and hold [E] for 1 second to start a Roll right rate.]
[Press and hold [Q] for 1 second to stop Roll right rate. Return back 0 degree roll.]
[Press and hold [D] for 1 second to start Yaw right rate.]
[Press and hold [A] for 1 second to stop Yaw left rate.]
[Command the spacecraft back to 0,0,0.]
[Switch to Rate Command.]

[Press and hold [S] to pitch up. Monitor it builds rates to 3 deg/sec then drifts until you release the stick, where it will damp the rates. Do the same for pitch down using [W] and return the craft to 0,0,0]

[Press and hold [E] to roll right. Monitor it builds rates to 3 deg/sec then drifts until you release the stick, where it will damp the rates. Do the same for roll left using [Q] and return the craft to 0,0,0]

[Press and hold [D] to yaw right. Monitor it builds rates to 3 deg/sec then drifts until you release the stick, where it will damp the rates. Do the same for yaw left using [A] and return the craft to 0,0,0]
Rate Command looks good. The control checks are completed.
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM.
Roger. Control checks are completed and insertion checklist is completed too.
Roger. Understand. I've been advised from the Cape you might put your prop switch off and recycle a couple of times, and it might stop your leak. Did you copy, Molly Brown?
I copy.
[Continue to maneuver as required, by using Pulse for example.]
We are over Africa, John.
Yes.
If you'll give me the camera, I'll take a couple of pictures.
Okay.
[Observe and take some photographs of Africa.]

MissionCommands.Comment: [Failure: Fail the Primary DC-to-DC. Make sure a bool function retruns true if either prim or sec is powered, and if not, all gauges are pegged or something.]

MissionCommands.Message: Look at the cabin pressure!
What?
We've lost the..
Lost what? What have we lost?
Lost a primary converter.
Are you sure you didn't bump the converter to the OFF position?
That switch way up there?
No, you couldn't, could you?
No.
Want to try it back on the primary and see what happens?
That's how we lost it. Yes.
See?
Yes.
Okay. That did it.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Cape CAP COM, Molly Brown here.
Roger. How's your status on that thruster?
It's still GO. We're still drifting a little bit, Gordo. It's not bad. I can hold it with Pulse with no problem. But we did lose our primary dc-dc converter.
Roger. Lost your primary dc-dc.
Molly Brown, have you tried your circuit breaker to cut off that one erratic thruster.
Negative.
Yaw left. It would be either OAMS No. 7 or 8.
[Observe that thrust is still building]
[Manually control the thrust using PULSE and try to keep 0, 0, 0.]
Hey! We're coming in on the night side.
Molly Brown, Cap CAP COM.
I ready you okay, Gordo.
Roger. How's your control system? I'm reading you weak but readable.
Yes, you are almost unreadable.
Say again, Molly Brown.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM. Say again.
I said I can barely read you, Gordo.
Roger, I'm barely reading you also.
How is your control system? Over.
[Mission Control internal for context: Let's leave him alone, we will try again at CSQ]
What time is it?
41 elapsed. I get CSQ at 42:19.
Okay.
About another minute.
Molly Brown, Molly Brown, CSQ CAP COM.
CSQ, this is Molly Brown.
Roger. How is your control system working?
Well, the control system is working fine. It's just that I have a very slight yaw to the left.
Roger. Understand. Would you confirm that you are on secondary dc-to-dc converter?
Affirmative.
Are you on secondary ACME yaw logic?
Negative.
Molly Brown, CSQ CAP COM. Are you in the FLOW position on the radiator?
Radiator is in FLOW position. We're trying ACME yaw logic, secondary yaw logic now.
Roger.
[Maneuver to 0, 0, 0 and go to Pulse and observe if yaw drift occurs]
Cape recommends that you place the driver switch to secondary.
Roger.
[Maneuver to 0,0,0 and observe if yaw drift is corrected.]

[The drift issue is still present, hold 0,0,0 using PULSE. Unrealistic: If it is tiresome, I have applied logic that prevents this from happening if you use rate command (the yaw issue lasted for the entire GT-3 mission).]

MissionCommands.Message: Molly Brown, CSQ.
Go ahead.
We have not received a blood pressure or an oral temp.
Roger. I told you the blood pressure bulb won't fit in the hole anymore. I think the O Ring is jammed, or something.
Roger.
Molly Brown, CSQ. Stand by for a GMT time hack. On my mark GMT will be 15 11 10.
MARK.
Roger your mark.
Have you received oral temp yet?
We copied your respiratory maneuver, and we have your oral temp. All systems appear GO from the ground.
Molly Brown, Molly Brown, Carnarvon CAP COM. How do you read?
Loud and clear. How me?
Roger. Read you the same. Could you give us your status please? And the cape would like to know if any of the remedies helped your yaw problem.
No. None of the remedies helped and we are GO.
Okay. You have a GO from down here for the second orbit, and, if you'll stand by, I'll send you a 2-1 Tr and a Gemini load.
Roger.
Stand by for Tr.
You ready?
Yes.
Okay, Molly Brown. We got your Gemini load. We could not get Tr in. We got a spacecraft reject on Tr, and it did go in at this time. I'd like to give you a hack on Tr at 39:30, in about 10 seconds.
You're going to punch it, aren't you? [On the MDIU, key CLEAR 1 9, and on MARK, press READ OUT.]
Yes.
Molly Brown, stand by on my mark. MARK! 39:30 is your Tr. Your Tr clock is synched with outs on the ground, and your spacecraft elapsed time is synched.
Roger, and I believe I see a light from Perth.
And if John is ready to copy any of this maneuver load, I have it for you.
[Press ROGER when you are ready to copy the maneuver pad.]
All set.
He's ready to copy.

Okay. GMTB 15 43 23. V of 139. Duration of burn, 2 minutes 39 seconds. Your GMTRC 15 55 24. Roll left 55. GMTRB 16 05 28. Roll right 65. GMT 400 K 15 58 23. Your maneuver load: 6344257, 0444775, 0533348, 664903.3, 676628.4, 082244.4, 09120.50, 10031.38, 11302.00. [Press COPY when complete]
Roger. Copied your parameters. Over.
Molly Brown, Carnarvon here. You can go secondary coolant loop OFF, and you can go evaporator to NORMAL.
Roger. Secondary coolant loop OFF and evaporator to NORMAL.
Molly Brown, Carnarvon CAP COM.
Go ahead.
Roger. Your Texas burn will be 48 ft/sec for 73 seconds.
Okay, 48 ft/sec for 73 seconds.
That's affirmative. We got your TR and Gemini load in. Your clocks look good on the ground, and everything is GO here. See you next trip.
Roger.
[Flight plan: RCS Plume Observation.]
[In this test you will fire all the attitude control thrusters, one axis at a time. During a burst, observe if the thrusters generate any visible lights out the window.]
[Switch to DIRECT mode and make bursts, one axis at a time. Pitch up, pitch down, roll left, roll right, yaw left, yaw right. Press START to begin.].
[When complete, bring the craft to 0,0,0.]
On the OAMS thruster check, the fire is red in streaks. When the yaw thrusters fire it definitely wipes out the horizon. Can see the horizon all right through the pitch thrusters.
Now we have a Catch-Up Mode Check.
Okay. You want to go to CATCH-UP?
Yes.
In CATCH-UP. That right?
[During GT-3, program load was instant as only a couple of programs were needed and they all fit in the memory. The CATCH-UP module is loaded instantly.]
Okay, and you've got the sea urchin eggs coming up at 1:15, too.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM here.
Cape CAP COM, Molly Brown. Go ahead.

Roger, Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM. We're going to have you leave your propellant switch on and do the Texas burn, and we will watch your fuel usage in across the States. If it continues, we'll have you turn your propellant switches off, then, when you're over the Cape next time, except when you need to use the fuel.
Leave the propellant switch on for the Texas burn, and then watch for leakage?
Roger. Leave it on till after the Texas burn, and then we will watch your leakage. If it continues to leak, we will have you turn them off over the Cape.
Roger. We can't tell that we're using any fuel.
Okay, fine. We are not overly concerned. It's just that we'd like to get a handle on what is causing it here.
Look at the sunrise.
Yes.
We have got to get ready for this Texas burn.
Yes.
What time is that Texas burn?
Here comes the sunrise. Is that beautiful!
Isn't that pretty?
Aren't you going to take any pictures?
I hadn't planned to on this pass. I'll get the camera out.
What did he say that burn was? It's 48 ft.
48 feet and 73 seconds.
Okay. you put that in, don't you?
Yes.
[Punch in the data into the OBC. On the MDUI, key CLEAR 0100133 ENTER CLEAR 2590480 ENTER CLEAR 2600000 ENTERCLEAR 2700000 ENTER CLEAR]
We'll be coming up for Guaymas, I guess, next.
Molly Brown, Molly Brown, RKV.
RKV, this is Molly Brown.
Roger. Read you loud and clear. I'm going to update your Tr and transmit a maneuver load to you.
Roger.
Roger, and I have transmitted a Tr and Gemini load for your maneuver over Corpus. Confirm you were in CATCH-UP. Over.
We're in CATCH-UP
Roger. You have a load in the CATCH-UP for your maneuver. You are GO for the next orbit.
Your ground elapsed time to burn, 01 33 00. Your V of the burn, 048. Your length of burn, 01:14.
Roger. We copied 15:57, 01:33, 48ft/sec, at a minute and 14 seconds.
Will you give me a readout of core 25, 26, and 27? Over. [Tranmission lost.]
Molly Brown, RKV CAP COM.
Go ahead RKV, Molly Brown.
Will you give me a readout of your computer core 25, 26, and 27, please?
[On the MDIU, check core 25,26,27 by keying: CLEAR 25 READ OUT, check value, CLEAR 26 READ OUT, check value, CLEAR 27 READ OUT, check value. Press DONE when complete]
Roger. It was.. 25 was minus 0480. 26 and 27 were all zeros. Over.
That is affirmative. I concur.
Molly Brown, can you give me a readout of your OAMS helium source pressure, temperature, and your propellant quantity gage.
The propellant quantity gage is 83 percent. Stand by, John will give you the other.
Roger. Source pressure is 2450. Source temperature is 85, and fuel and oxidizer regulated at 295 with 68.
Roger.
Molly Brown, stand by for Guaymas.
Roger.
Outstanding! I see the whole of Mexico.
Molly Brown, Guaymas CAP COM.
Molly Brown, Guaymas handing over to Texas.
Roger.
[The computer should now calculate and set up for the burn using the 0100133 2590480 2600000 2700000]
You'll give me a mark now on my burn. Right?
Roger.
Okay. It will be about two minutes before we start it. So you punch off your stopwatch and give me a mark to stop it, just in case it doesn't go to zero.
Okay.
Molly Brown, Texas CAP COM.
Read you loud and clear, Texas.
Roger. Texas standing by for your maneuver.
Roger.
[Use rate command and maneuver to 0,0,0, you should already be pretty close. You can then maneuver so the entire dV is in the AFT IVI display]
How we doing on time?
Fine.
Twenty seconds to burn. You copy that, Texas?
Roger.
Okay. 3 seconds.
MARK! [Start the burn, use translation thrusters to zero the IVIs]
Roger. Texas confirms OAMS thruster firing.
Molly Brown, how are your attitudes holding?
Perfect.
[Press ROGER when the burn is complete]
Thrusting complete.
Roger. Confirmed maneuver complete.
Okay, Molly Brown. Looks like your OAMS has leveled out before your burn. Can you give us an OAMS source pressure and temp again now?
This source pressure is 2050. Source temperature is 56.
Roger.
I have a time for you, where you will be nearest to the booster. Would you like to have that so you can look for it?
Roger.
Roger. 02 + 08 + 52. Will be dead ahead at an elevation of plus 80 at 190 miles. This will be just prior to darkness. It should be very bright. Proceed to see if you can rendezvous.
Roger.
We are sending you a load now.

MissionCommands.Comment: [Send updated Tr value, Tr value should be 02HH, 28MM, 35SS]

MissionCommands.Message: Roger, DCS load received.

MissionCommands.Comment: [Send another DCS value. Tr value should be 02HH, 28MM, 35SS]

MissionCommands.Message: I had another DCS load just in, too.
Roger. That was the actual values. The first one was the Tr.
Roger.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM. Did you get your experiments for the first orbit?
Roger. We got them on time for the first orbit.
Roger. Everything looks good down here.
Roger.
You still got a blood pressure, John? We didn't read it.
He sent it, okay. I'll give you another one.
Okay. Just wondered if he was breathing.
Gordo, do you have me a time for the Horizon Scan Check?
Cape CAP COM, do you read, Molly Brown.
Go ahead Molly Brown. Cape CAP COM.
Do you have me a time for the Horizon Scanner Check?
Okay, sunset time is 16 + 34. Stand by, and I will get you the horizon scanner.
That is the time for it, Molly Brown. 16 + 34.
Roger.
Pretty spectacular up there, huh?
Yeah, it really is. It really is!
We didn't get to see much of the States though.
Clouded over? Too many clouds, huh? [LOS, Bermuda]
Let's see, do you want your meal? [This starts the Food Evaluation for John, and Alignment Check for Gus]
Yes.
Is this one all right?
Yes, this is the one here.
You can't get the bulb in, huh? How about if I just leave it in and give them blood pressures.
Yes, go ahead.
Hot dog! Good old food.
Going to have to make Alignment Check.
Want to just slap those babies over there?
They said to leave the brownies closed.
Okay, starting Alinement Caging Check.
[Align the craft with the horizon]
Going to CAGE, small-end-forward, holding attitudes out the window.
Okay, I've caged.
Going SEF, platform and attitude.
Fine aline from 1:45 to 1:55. [Leave it in SEF]
Let me have some of that juice when you get done.
Get any water?
Good stuff!
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM.
Canary CAP COM, Molly Brown. Go ahead.
Roger. We have systems GO on the ground.
Roger. We are GO in here. We are finishing our Alinement Check.
Roger. Understand
What was the time we could see that booster?
Molly Brown, Canary CAP COM.
Go, Canaries.
Roger. After your burn your orbit is 85.6, 92.6. [This will differ depending on your insertion (where Pe was) and the execution of the burn itself]
And I have a Two-Bravo time.
Standby.
[Press READY when you are ready to copy]
Okay. What's the Two-Bravo time?
Roger. V90. GMTRC 16 52 25. GETRC 02 28 35. Roll left 55.
[Copy V90. GMTRC 16 52 25. GETRC 02 28 35. Roll left 55.]
Roger. Two-Bravo: 90 V. 16 52 25 GMTRC. Elapsed time of 02 28 25. Roll left 55.
That's affirm.
What is it?
Corn beef sandwich.
Where did that come from?
I brought it with me. Let's see how it tastes. Smells, doesn't it?
Yes, it's breaking up. I'm going to stick it in my pocket.
Is it?
It was a thought, anyways.
Yep.
Not a very good one.
Pretty good, though, if it would just hold together.
Want some chicken leg?
No, you can handle that.
What was the time of that booster again? What elevation?
2 hours, 8 minutes, 52 seconds. 18 el.
We're alined just about perfect. What do you think, looking out your window?
Yeah, man. That's beautiful!
What else have we got to do? Scanners should be on secondary. Now we're going to yaw 180 here.
[Using direct, start a 180 degree yaw drift rate to look in the retrograde direction]
Hey, look out there. There's some land. Must still be over Canaries.
You're a noisy eater.
[Press ROGER when you are at 180 degrees of yaw and have stopped the rates.]
How do you like this going backwards? You can tell you're going backwards too, can't you?
Never a doubt.
That's not bad for applesauce.
I'll take a bite of applesauce, if you don't eat it all.
It's getting tough to squeeze out of there.
If we had some pork chops to go with it, we'd be all right.
Yes.
Let's see what my retrofire attitude looks like going backwards.
Okay. 16 nose down is what it is.
[Maneuver to 16 nose down while at 180 yaw to visually observe what retro fire attitude looks like. Press ROGER when done.]
I'll tell you, man, you don't need anything to tell your yaw, do you?
No, I'll tell you, I need some of these missions where I can look out of the window. I haven't looked out of this window a second and a half. It's beautiful!
[Manuever 60 degrees left, then return to center, and then manuever 60 degrees right, observe ground track relative to yaw.]
[Return back to 180 yaw for the horizon scanner check]
The sun's hot.
It is. [Prepare for Horizon Scanner check a 2:07:49]
Okay, let's start this thing right now. [Center the sun in the window.]
Okay, it's pitching up slightly. Going up above zero. I don't have a scanner light. Man, is it dark!
[Mark the yaw as you point towards the sun. Yaw 5 degrees left of the sun and stop rates.]
[Establish a 5 deg/sec yaw right rate and stop it at 5 degrees yaw right of the sun]
[Return to 0 degrees yaw and align with the horizon]
What time is it in the flight plan?
2 hours and 10 minutes.
You're supposed to give an oral temperature.
I'll give them one.
Okay. Translation Check at 2:17, which is 7 minutes away.
[Maneuver to 90 Yaw. The maneuver will be an out-of-plane burn at GET 02:17:00. You will fire the fwd thrusters for 16 seconds [H], followed by 2 seconds on the aft thrusters [N].]
Molly Brown, CSQ CAP COM. Do you read?
CSQ CAP COM, Molly Brown.
Roger read you weak but clear. We have you green from the ground.
Roger. Getting ready for a translation burn.
Molly Brown, CSQ CAP COM. We're standing by for the maneuver.
5 seconds. [Prepare to fire the FWD thrsuters]
[Burn! Fire the thrusters until John says MARK]
MARK! [Stop the burn]
[Burn 1 second using the AFT thrusters [N], press DONE when complete.]
Burn complete. That was with a 90 yaw.
Molly Brown, CSQ. How did your attitudes hold during the maneuver?
Attitudes held very well.
Roger. You still look real good from the ground here.
[Switch to PULSE and start the platform alignment procedure - complete it during the next conversation. Align with the horizon, set the scanners to CAGE below SEF, then return them to SEF.]
Molly Brown, Molly Brown, Carnarvon CAP COM. How do you read? [No audio for the next conversation]
Carnarvon, this is Molly Brown. Read you loud and clear.
Very good, Gus. We'd like to get a blood pressure on the co-pilot, please, and could I have your status?
Okay - blood pressure's coming and our status is green.

Very good. We don't have any communications with the Cape at this time, but they have requested for me to run down your flight control problem a little bit. The first thing I'd like to know is what kind of rates are you getting if you just let it yaw?
They are very slow, Pete. Probably on the order of a quarter of a degree per second.
Okay and you are in a horizon scan mode, is that correct?
At the present time I'm in Pulse and alining the platform.
Okay. You're in pulse alining the platform.
Are your ACME logic yaw rate gyros and attitude drivers and all that stuff still primary?
Affirmative.
Okay, strike all that other stuff. It sounds to me like you've got a mechanical problem in the valve. Is that what you figured?
Roger, it must be very, very slight. We can't see the pressure go down.
Okay, and you have turned off 3, 4, 7 and 8 yaw circuit breakers and put them on again, and that didn't have any effect?
Yes, we've gone through everything, Pete.

Okay. That should keep them happy back there. We are not going to send you a load. Your TR is good. I don't have your clock counting down with mine. I guess you have a different one in. We got your blood pressure and your clocks are on as far as SET goes.
Roger.
You have a GO down here from everybody.
You're going to make these Horizon Scan Checks after a little bit?
Yes. You do it, because I'm busy here.
Molly Brown, this is Carnarvon. How do you read?
Still read you loud and clear.
Okay, you'll probably go over the hill, Gus. You look good here on the ground. We'll see you on your next go.
Roger, thank you, Pete.
Okay, what does the flight plan say about here, Gus?
I'm supposed to be doing the Horizon Scanner Check, but I don't have time to do it.
Oh, okay. Well thanks, I'm done. I'm supposed to be doing that O2 High Rate Check. Is it at 2:40 in the flight plan?
Yes. 2:40 right now.
Okay, we'll got to O2 High Rate.
Okay, MARK. O2 High Rate.
I'm sure uncomfortable.
Yes, it's bad.
[O2 HIGH RATE will increase O2 consumption and slowly build up cabin pressure until cabin relief kicks in. Leave it on.]
Man! The primary scanners are working! How about that!
Still don't have that scanner light out. [Press NOW when the primary scanner light is out (90 seconds)]
There it goes.
Okay, 2 minutes and 30 seconds O2 High Rate.
And the Greenwich mean time is 1707.
Okay, MARK.
O2 High Rate recocked.
[Do another platform alignment with the horizon]
Hello, Molly Brown. This is Hawaii CAP COM.
Hello, Hawaii. (This is Molly Brown.)
We are ready to uplink a 4-1 Tr to you.
Go ahead, send it.
Okay, sending, now.
Roger, 4-1 time received and verified.
Molly Brown, Cape, Uh, Hawaii CAP COM. Everything looks good on the ground. We will see you on the next time around. Aloha.
Roger.
[Maneuver to 0,0,0]
Molly Brown, RKV CAP COM. Over.
RKV, this is Molly Brown.
Roger. We are standing by for your respiratory maneuver.
Roger.
The respiratory maneuver? I can give it to them.
Here it comes.
Roger. We copy, Molly Brown. We are standing by for your pilot's oral temp and blood pressure.
Blood pressure is coming.
Roger.
Molly Brown, RKV. We have received your blood pressure and temperature.
Roger.
Molly Brown, RKV CAP COM.
Go ahead.
If you are drifting in Orbit Rate, suggest you select a mode of your own for your tracking task coming up on the coast.
Roger.
Molly Brown, RKV. You are looking good here on the ground. If you have any further comments we are standing by.
Negative.
Roger. Guaymas will be next.

[Next will be a Tracking Task to figure out how well you can track using the various control modes. You will center a landmark in the window, switch to ORB RATE or the mode of your choice, and then try to track the landmarks in direct first, then rate command, then pulse.]
[It is up to you to choose what landmark to track and what order the control mode is in. You will perform this excercise until you are back over Canaveral.]
I don't see a good target anyplace.
Can you pitch it down and toward the States, Gus?
Molly Brown, Guaymas CAP COM.
Guaymas, Molly Brown.
Your Three-Alpha times are nominal.
Roger, and nominal.
We are standing by for your coolant pump checks.
[Continue your tracking task]
What did you say, Guaymas?
We are standing by for your report on your Coolant Pump Checks.
Here, there is a target down there. [Just try to maneuver, not sure if this conversation makes sense, might remove it]
Where? I don't know what you see.
There's all kinds of stuff. See that town down there?
Where?
Right around here on the right.
I can't see over there, John. I'll roll back to the right so we can both see. Ah yeah, there is one right down below here. Let's see if I can get it.
Molley Brown, Guaymas.
Have you completed your Coolant Pump Checks?
[This starts the SEC/PRI Coolant Pump B checks. Pause the tracking task while you check if the coolant pumps B works.]
[Coolant Pump SEC B on]
[Coolant Pump SEC B off]
[Coolant Pump PRI B on]
[Coolant Pump PRI B off]
Tell them we have done our Coolant Pump Check.
Coolant Pump Checks (complete).
Roger. What is the status on the checks?
We couldn't get the pumps on simultaneously. (audio was just garble)
[Continue tracking task]
That is right up from the tip of the Gulf of California, isn't it?
Yes.
I don't see the Salton Sea.
Hey, Gus. We are coming up on El Paso.
Are we?
That's the mountain range right there. See that hill right over there? I think El Paso is under the clouds.
Molly Brown, Guaymas. Would you say again the trouble you are having with your pump check?
We had no trouble with the pump check.
Roger. Would you remove pump A off of primary?
Pump A is off primary.
[Align back to 0,0,0, this ends the Tracking Task]
Molly Brown. This is Guaymas handing you over to Texas.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Go ahead, Cape CAP COM.
What is the status of your other platform modes, such as BEF and Free?
Well SEF is fine. Orbit Rate is the one that drives me off in roll. I haven't checked BEF yet. I'll go ahead and give it a check now.
Okay. How long does it take you to build up this quarter degree rate in that yaw rate, starting from zero yaw rate?
Gordo, it just gradually accelerates. It's some slow leak out there.
[Check that the platform is aligned with BEF.]
Roger. Are you satisfied with obtaining and holding your attitudes visually?
Roger, and the platform is alining properly in SEF.
Okay, fine. You want to turn your standby transmitter off?
Standby transmitter off.
Okay. Have you tried secondary scanner?
Roger. We were on secondary scanner for quite awhile. We are back on primary now.
Okay, if you think the platform is drifting too much there for that Control Mode Characteristic Check, just delete that  that at 3 + 30.
Roger. I also, I deleted the, that one .. (Horizon Scanner Mode Check).
Okay. The one earlier?
Roger.
Okay. I have your 4-1 weather for you. It is broken cloud conditions. 20 miles visibility. Wind is 20 knots, at 5 foot seas.
Roger, 20 and 5 foot.
Roger. Did you have any success on contact with the booster?
We were facing the wrong way at that time, making a Horizon Scanner Check.
Yeah, I was afraid you would be. That was a little bit tight in there.
Did you manage to see anything over the U.S. because of the clouds?
We could see the southern part of California and Arizona, I guess. That was about it.
You want to get your real-time telemetry and acq aid on?
It's on.
How's the weather, in general, around the world?
Very cloudy.
I see.
[Test the FREE mode a bit]
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Go ahead Cape.
Have you had a chance to check that Free mode yet?
I'm in Free mode now, and it looks like it is working all right.
Very good. We were sure interested in that.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Go ahead.
That next normal burn will be a V of 96. The time on that is 1 + 49.
Roger. 96 ft/sec and 1 + 49 seconds.

[Due to a bad tape change, the recorder did not function again until 04 08 00. We will get comms back in about 30 minutes. For now, no transcript exists. We will complete the Flight Plan items until then.]
[Flight plan, 3:15:00 - Platform Stabilization Check]
[Switch to BEF. Check if platform is stable during maneuvering. Remain in BEF when complete and use timescale to next instruction at 3:30:00]
[Flight plan, 3:30:00 - Backup CO2 Sensor Check, skip]
Molly Brown, CSQ CAP COM.
CSQ, this is Molly Brown. Go ahead.
Roger. What's the status?
We are GO.
Roger. You look good from the ground. Stand by to copy Three-Bravo times.
Roger. We are ready.
GMTRC 18 37 58. Ground elapsed time 04 13 58. Bank angle, roll left 55. V 93. Molly Brown, CSQ. Did you copy?
[Copy GMTRC 18 37 58. Ground elapsed time 04 13 58. Bank angle, roll left 55. V 93.]
Roger. GMTRC is 18 37 58. Bank angle, 55 left. V 93.
Molly Brown, CSQ CAP COM. Cape recommends you perform your OAMS retroburn in BEF after alinement, and stay in BEF up to retrofire.
Roger. Agree with that.
[Flight Plan: 3:50:00 - Preretro Checklist]

[Complete the initial steps of the checklist with the exception of time scaling/setting the event timer (do not time scale to Tr -20:00). Complete the other steps until step RE-ENT module loads: Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Entry: PRE RETRO, use either the RUN feature or complete it manually. Press DONE when complete.]
Molly Brown, CSQ. Did you finish your retrofire checklist?
Roger.
We are standing by for your Sea Urchin Egg Experiment.
Roger. It's being activated.
Roger.
Molly Brown, Molly Brown, Carnarvon. CAP COM. Over.
Carnarvon, Molly Brown.
Roger. Read you loud and clear. We are going to send you a new 4-1 command load and Tr. Do you have your timer set at 34:00?
[Ensure Event Timer is set to stop, then set the Event Timer to 34 minutes, counting down. Press DONE when complete.]
Timer set at 34:00.
Okay. In the meantime I'd like to get helium source temperature, pressure, and quantity reading from you.
OAMS propellant quantity is 55 percent. Source pressure is 1950. Source temperature is 81. [These values will differ from your execution]
Roger. Thank you. Command load coming.
If you are looking at the ground, Molly Brown, Carnarvon has a big fire going for you down here.
We are blunt-end-forward. We can't see them yet.
Okay.
Molly Brown, Carnarvon CAP COM. We have a GO here on the ground, and I have about 1 minute, 30 seconds till your time hack.
Roger.
Molly Brown, Carnarvon CAP COM. Stand by for Tr MARK of 34:00, in approximately 30 seconds.
[Be prepared to start the event timer on MARK]
Roger. The clock is counting down.
What is the GMT of retrofire you just gave us?
Roger. The GMTRC is 18 57 23 for a GETRC of 04 33 23.
Cape recommends that I give you your backup quantities there for GMTRC of 18 57 23. It'll be a roll left 55. GMTRB of 19 08 23. Roll right 65 at GMT 400K 19 01 29.
We got it, Pete.
Okay, Gus. I only have one question for you before you go out of range. [Garble]
[Garble]
[Garble] GT-3. See you next trip, next year!
Okay.
Okay. That was the last tape change. [Ok, new tape and issue resolved, we should now have transcription in]
The last burn we received was 96 feet a second and a minute and 49 seconds of burn. Right?
Yeah, we're going to aline.
[Switch to CATCHUP, and press ROGER to receive burn data to punch into the OBC]
[CLEAR 0100421 ENTER CLEAR 0202300 ENTER CLEAR 2590960 ENTER CLEAR 2600000 ENTER CLEAR 2700000 ENTER]
[This burn will bring Pe down into the atmosphere in case the retro engines fails. The new Pe will be around 39-42 nmi.]
Okay. Ready for this burn.
I've got to start that computer.
Man! There's the horizon and it is beautiful.
[Align so the IVIs has everything in FWD/AFT. Ensure you are looking retrograde (yaw 180) and you will perform a retrograde burn by thrusting in the forward S/C direction [H] ]
Hello, Molly Brown. Hawaii CAP COM.
Hawaii, Molly Brown, all is clear.
Roger. Give us a hack on your event timer.
Okay, it'll be 12:55 on my mark.
MARK.
Okay. On my IVI's, I have 97 ft/sec forward and the others are zips.
Roger, and give us a mark for the start of burn.
Roger. We've got about 25 seconds to go.
10 seconds.
MARK!
[Zero the IVIs]
Yes, it's burning.
[Complete the burn. Press DONE when it is complete]
MARK! End of burn.
Right. Mark end of burn. Good show.
[Using the map view, tweak so your Pe is at 39 nmi alt]
Now we can go to REENTRY. Right?
Yes.
[Start to execute the Tr-5 (256 seconds) checklist. You can use the RUN feature or complete it manually]
Molly Brown, RKV CAP COM.
Read you loud and clear, RKV.
Roger. Have you completed Tr-5 checklist?
[Press ROGER when you have completed the checklist]
TR-5 is complete.
You want to mark at Tr-1 minute?
Not necessary.
Roger.
Molly Brown, RKV. You look good from the ground.
Roger.
[RUN or Manually go through the Tr-1 minute checklist]
Five seconds to one minute. MARK!
Separate OAMS? Separate electronics, separate adapter.
Yes, go ahead.
Hey, the adapter has separated.
Roger, we confirm on the ground. Adapter sep.
Yes, you can really feel it.
[Continue the checklist, prepare for retro fire]
[Retro 1,2,3,4 fire sequence]
All rockets fired normally and attitudes were right in the center.
Roger. Pass your IVI readouts on to Guaymas. RKV out.
[Continue with the checklist]
Molly Brown, Guaymas CAP COM. Do you copy?
Roger, Guaymas. The IVI's readings were 331 Aft, 105 Right, and 4 Up. Right in the center. An automatic superfine retrofire down the line.
Retropack has jettisoned.
Roger.
[Start to go through the POST RETRO JETTISON checklist]
Molly Brown, Guaymas CAP COM.
Go, Guaymas.
I'm prepared to give you a Tr + 3 minute time hack if you need it?
That would be good.
Okay, and I have some event times for reentry: 400K feet 19 10 29. Molly Brown, correction on 400K feet of 19 01 29.
Roger.
Molly Brown, I'll give you a time hack in approximately 30 seconds.
Molly Brown, Guaymas. Stand by for a TR + 3 minute time hack.
5, 4, 3, 2, 1, MARK. Do you copy?
Roger. We got it.
Molly Brown, stand by for Texas.
Roger.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Molly Brown here, go ahead.
Roger. I'm getting your bank angle times momentarily. Your start of Communications Experiment is 19 05 14.
Molly Brown, I have your backup times on the bank angles and time to reverse bank angle.
Go ahead.
Bank left 45. Bank right 55. Time to reverse bank angle 19 08 17.
Give me an elapsed time after retro.
Time from retro fire to reverse bank angle is 10:54. Ten minutes, 54 seconds.
Cape CAP COM. Transmitting to you in blackout for Communications Experiment. Over. [Probably not heard by crew]
That was an end of that.
Molly Brown, are you reading Cape CAP COM now? Over.
Roger. We're down to 80 000 feet. My needles show us about 25 miles short.
[Start to go through the LANDING checklist.]
Reading alt 60 000.
There goes the drogue.
Roger.
Okay, we have a drogue.
Roger, drogue. Looks pretty good, doesn't it?
Our propellant valves are shut off. We've got a 40K light. Really oscillating.
Roger.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM. How is your main?
We don't have a main yet. Passing through 13 000.
Molly Brown, how is your main. Over? [LOS]
Okay. We have a good stable chute. Going to landing attitude.
[With the Main Chutes deployed, switch to Landing Attitude. Press DONE when complete]
Oh, man! That was the roughest one of the whole bunch, wasn't it!?
Oh man! [The Landing Att orientation change for so impulsive that Gus hit the panels so hard the visor cracked]
Okay. We all set?
Yes. Now we go through the post-main checklist.
[Continue to follow the landing checklist]
Let's see, can they read us now?
Cape CAP COM, this is Molly Brown.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM.
Intrepid [Recovery], this is Molly Brown.
Roger. We are reading you now and then. How us?
Loud and clear. I have 30 ft/sec rate of descent. Passing through 5500.
Roger, 5500.
You never took your D-Ring out, huh?
Yes I did, too!
Oh, did you?
You better believe it!
Face plate open?
Open?
That's what the checklist says.
Molly Brown, Cape CAP COM. The carrier have set up a communicationw lockdown with you over there.
Molly Brown, this is Intrepid. It appears you will land 5 miles ahead of me. Over.
Roger. Thank you.
Do you have us in sight, Intrepid?
Not yet. Over.
Roger.
Passing through 4000.
Do you smell that fuel? Fumes from that stuff?
Yes. Let's close up.
Yes. I can see 'em smoking out there.
We're coming through the lower layer, John. You better get ready to hit. We're at 2000. No telling how far the altimeter is off.
Okay. I'm as ready as I'll ever be.
You can put your head back.
Landing attitude was a bump, wasn't it?
Yes.
We're at 1500 feet. We're in good shape.
Broke my face plate when we went to landing attitude.
Did it?
This is Molly Brown in the water. Anybody read?
Molly Brown, this is Big Box 15. You are loud and clear. Check with Big Box 14.
Roger. We're floating well in the water.
[This completes the mission. I will add more audio if I discover the missing tapes or pieces. Good job on completing this mission!]

Title: GT-3: The Molly Brown
Description: GT-3 was the first manned mission in NASA's Gemini program, the second American manned space program. Astronauts Gus Grissom and John Young will be flying three low Earth orbits in their spacecraft, which they nicknamed Molly Brown, with the main objectives of testing the new Gemini spacecraft.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

Gemini III is set to launch at 09:24 am from Launch Complex 19 at Cape Kennedy, Florida.
The spaceship will launch into orbit where various tests will be performed. The spaceship will orbit Earth three times before reentry and splashdown.
